es to an increasingly hostile National Socialist environment. These writings offer a challenging model of intellectual engagement, one that remains as compelling today as it was in Auerbach's own time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aCriticismzGermany. 0aCriticszGermany. 0aLiterary historianszGermany. 0aLiteraturexHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Comparative Literature.2bisacsh  aAeneid.  aAllegory.  aAntonomasia.  aAthalie.  aAvitus of Vienne.  aBlaise Pascal.  aBook.  aChristianity.  aChurch Fathers.  aClassical Latin.  aClassical Philology (journal).  aClassical language.  aClassicism.  aConsummation.  aCultural history.  aDe Monarchia.  aDemocritus.  aDialectic.  aDivine law.  aEclecticism.  aEnglish poetry.  aErich Auerbach.  aEssays (Montaigne).  aEtymology.  aForm of life (philosophy).  aG. (novel).  aGenre.  aGiambattista Vico.  aGod.  aHermeneutics.  aHistorical fiction.  aHistorical figure.  aHistorical linguistics.  aHistorical method.  aHistorical realism.  aHistoricism.  aHistoricity.  aHistoriography.  aHistorism.  aHumanities.  aIn Parenthesis.  aIntellectual history.  aJacques Maritain.  aJean Bolland.  aJean-Jacques Rousseau.  aJohann Georg Hamann.  aKarl Kraus (writer).  aLactantius.  aLate Antiquity.  aLeveling (philosophy).  aLiterary criticism.  aLiterature.  aLucretius.  aMagnificence (history of ideas).  aMajor Publications.  aMedieval literature.  aMedieval poetry.  aMeister Eckhart.  aMetonymy.  aMichel de Montaigne.  aMysticism.  aNarrative.  aNeoplatonism.  aNominalism.  aNovum.  aOf Education.  aOld Testament.  aPerspectivism.  aPetrarch.  aPhilology.  aPhilosophy of history.  aPhilosophy.  aPlautus.  aPoetry